Autoimmune pancreatitis: an adolescent case and review of literature. We present a case of a 16-year-old adolescent boy with autoimmune pancreatitis and a review of the related literature. The patient was sent from a peripheral medical center, presenting with jaundice, pruritus, weight loss, and hyperglycemia of 20 days' duration. At admission, the patient was icteric, choluric, and acholic. His abdomen was soft and nontender, and the patient felt no pain in his abdomen. He had skin lesions because of scratching. Laboratory findings showed a blood glucose level of 135 mg% total serum bilirubin, 29.4 mg%